      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Forget About the Deer,'' by Daniel Cameron (Op-Ed, July 18):</p>
        <p>My wife, my three children and I have all had Lyme disease. Our concern in guarding against this dreadful disease is constant.</p>
        <p>Dr. Cameron's suggestion, ''spraying yards with the pesticides carbaryl and granular deltamethrin once or twice a year,'' worried me. Carbaryl produces tumors in lab animals and is shown to produce developmental toxicity in a number of species, including mallards, bobwhite quail, trout and sunfish. Deltamethrin is very toxic to aquatic organisms, and while it may target ticks, it will also target the central nervous system and cardiovascular system of humans. Both are also dangerous for the environment.</p>
        <p>I am troubled, too, by Dr. Cameron's call to remove birdfeeders from our backyards. Seeing my kids at the windows in our home identifying seasonal and migratory species of birds at our feeders is something that thrills me. Every parent should get to experience this educational joy.</p>
        <p>These diseases are worrisome, but poisons and the elimination or even controlled reduction of our connection to the natural world are more deadly and not the solution to any problem.</p>
        <p>William Abranowicz  Bedford</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
